Wash and dry produce.

Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}. Halve, core, and thinly slice
@long green pepper{1}.

In a #medium bowl{}, toss together @shredded red cabbage{4%ounce}, half the
@rice wine vinegar{5%teaspoon} (all for 4 servings), half the cilantro,
@sugar{1.5%teaspoon} (2 tsp for 4), and a pinch of @salt{} until thoroughly
combined.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high
heat. Add green pepper and cook, stirring, until slightly softened,
~{2-3%minutes}.

Add @ground turkey{10%ounce} and season with salt and @pepper{}. Cook,
breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through,
~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir in @sweet soy glaze{2 1/2%tablespoon} (5 TBSP for 4 servings) and
@sugar{1/2%teaspoon} (1 tsp for 4). Cook until everything is coated and glaze
has thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}. Remove from heat.

> Open package of turkey and drain off any excess
> liquid. Swap in chicken or turkey* for beef. (No need to
> break up chicken into pieces!)

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon} with
@sriracha{1%teaspoon} to taste. Season with salt and pepper.

Wrap @flour tortillas{6} in damp #paper towels{} and microwave until
warm and pliable, ~{30%seconds}.

Divide tortillas between plates and fill with beef stir-fry
and slaw (draining first). Top with Sriracha mayo,
@wonton strips{1%ounce}, and remaining cilantro. Serve.

> Ground Turkey is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.